{
  "query": "What are the most beneficial actions for reducing human-wildlife conflict with bears?",
  "answer": "The most beneficial actions for reducing human-wildlife conflict with bears include providing alternative food sources and using deterrents.\n\nProviding diversionary feeding for mammals has been shown to reduce nuisance behaviour by black bears in some studies (2323). In one instance, a significant portion of the diet of brown bears was composed of provided diversionary food, suggesting it can be a primary method of managing their feeding habits (2323). Another approach is to issue enforcement notices for non bear-proof garbage dumpsters, although the effectiveness of this action is currently unknown (2345). Additionally, the use of conditioned taste aversion has been found to be likely to be beneficial in reducing human-wildlife conflict in non-residential sites (2384). Studies have shown that lacing foodstuffs with substances that induce illness can lead to those foods being avoided by black bears (2384).",
